text: Metric-Based Analysis of Convergence in Complex Molecule Synthesis Published as part of the Accounts of Chemical Research special issue “Total Synthesis of Natural Products”. and Seth B. Herzon*

CONSPECTUS: Convergent syntheses are characterized by the coupling of two or more synthetic intermediates of similar complexity, often late in a pathway. At its limit, a fully convergent synthesis is achieved when commercial or otherwise readily available intermediates are coupled to form the ﬁnal target in a single step. Of course, in all but exceptional circumstances this level of convergence is purely hypothetical; in practice, additional steps are typically required to progress from fragment coupling to the target. Additionally, the length of the sequence required to access each target is a primary consideration in synthetic design. In this Account, we provide an overview of alkaloid, polyketide, and diterpene metabolites synthesized in our laboratory and present parameters that may be used to put the degree of convergence of each synthesis on quantitative footing. We begin with our syntheses of the antiproliferative, antimicrobial bacterial metabolite (−)-kinamycin F (1) and related dimeric structure (−)-lomaiviticin aglycon (2). These synthetic routes featured a three-step sequence to construct a complex diazocyclopentadiene found in both targets and an oxidative dimerization to unite the two halves of (−)-lomaiviticin aglycon (2). We then follow with our synthesis of the antineurodegenerative alkaloid (−)-huperzine A (3). Our route to (−)-huperzine A (3) employed a diastereoselective three- component coupling reaction, followed by the intramolecular α-arylation of a β-ketonitrile intermediate, to form the carbon skeleton of the target. We then present our syntheses of the hasubanan alkaloids (−)-hasubanonine (4), (−)-delavayine (5), (−)-runanine (6), (+)-periglaucine B (7), and (−)-acutumine (8). These alkaloids bear a 7-azatricyclo[4.3.3.01,6]dodecane (propellane) core and a highly oxidized cyclohexenone ring. The propellane structure was assembled by the addition of an aryl acetylide to a complex iminium ion, followed by intramolecular 1,4-addition

.01,6]dodecane (propellane) core and a highly oxidized cyclohexenone ring. The propellane structure was assembled by the addition of an aryl acetylide to a complex iminium ion, followed by intramolecular 1,4-addition. We then present our synthesis of the guanidinium alkaloid (+)-batzelladine B (9), which contains two complex polycyclic guanidine residues united by an ester linkage. This target was logically disconnected by an esteriﬁcation to allow for the independent synthesis of each guanidine residue. A carefully orchestrated cascade reaction provided (+)-batzelladine B (9) in a single step following fragment coupling by esteriﬁcation. We then discuss our synthesis of the diterpene fungal metabolite (+)-pleuromutilin (10). The synthesis of (+)-pleuromutilin (10) proceeded via a fragment coupling involving two neopentylic reagents and employed a nickel-catalyzed reductive cyclization reaction to close the eight-membered ring, ultimately providing access to (+)-pleuromutilin (10), (+)-12-epi-pleuromutilin (11), and (+)-12-epi-mutilin (12). Finally, we discuss our synthesis of (−)-myrocin G (13), a tricyclic pimarane diterpene that was assembled by a convergent annulation. In the ﬁnal section of this Account, we present several paramaters to analyze and quantitatively assess the degree of convergence of each synthesis. These parameters include: (1) the number of steps required following the point of convergence, (2) the diﬀerence in the number of steps required to prepare each coupling partner, (3) the percentage of carbons (or, more broadly, atoms) present at the point of convergence, and (4) the complexity generated in the fragment coupling step. While not an exhaustive list, these parameters bring the strengths and weaknesses each synthetic strategy to light, emphasizing the key contributors to the degree of convergence of each route while also highlighting the nuances of these analyses.

Our in developing laboratory has had a longstanding interest convergent syntheses of secondary metabolites and has focused on fragment coupling reactions in our synthetic planning. The concept of convergent synthesis has been discussed in several excellent reviews.5 Additionally, Hendrickson and Bertz have advanced quantitative methods to evaluate convergence and synthetic eﬃciency.6 In this Account, we codify intuitive parameters from which one can evaluate the convergence. While the obvious metrics employed for such analyses typically involve the number of steps to each fragment and the longest linear sequence to the target, we wish to evaluate convergence by considering the number of steps required after the point of convergence and the diﬀerence in the number of steps to each fragment. These two additional parameters provide a measure against the hypothetical, fully convergent approach outlined above. We also discuss the obvious metric of atoms introduced: an ideally convergent route should unite all of the atoms in the target. Finally, we consider the number of bonds, rings, and stereocenters introduced in a fragment coupling step. This provides a means to quantify the complexity generated, or, “what is gained” in a coupling. While additional measures can be easily envisioned (for example, the these introduction of strain elements), we believe that parameters provide an optimal balance between generality and accuracy of the analysis. We use syntheses completed in our laboratory (targets shown in Figure 1) to illustrate these parameters.

(−)-Kinamycin C (15) was ﬁrst synthesized by Porco and Lei in 2006.8 Subsequently, the ﬁrst synthesis of (−)-kinamycin F (1) was reported by Nicolaou and co-workers in 2007.9 Scully and Porco then disclosed the synthesis of epoxykinamycin (−)-FL-120B′ (17) in 2011.10 In 2011, we reported the enantioselective synthesis of (−)-kinamycin F (1).11 The key strategic element in our synthesis involved the formation of the central diazocyclopentadiene residue by coupling O-(methoxymethyl)-3-bromo-2-methoxy-juglone (18) and the γ-trimethylsilyl-α,β-unsaturated ketone 19, followed by ring closure and diazo transfer.

O-(Methoxymethyl)-3-bromo-2-methoxy-juglone (18) was prepared in three steps and 48% yield from juglone (20, Scheme 2a). The enantioenriched cyclohexenone 19 was prepared in six steps, 24% yield, and 97% ee from 3-(tri-iso-propylsilyloxy)- toluene (21). We found that the addition of the nucleophilic ﬂuoride source tris(diethylamino)sulfonium trimethyldiﬂuoro- silicate [TASF(Et)] to a solution of 18 and 19 promoted desilylative addition of 19 to quinone 18, with the elimination of methoxide, to generate the fragment coupling product 22 (79%, Scheme 2b). Attempts to couple the fragments via the formation of an extended enolate were unsuccessful, suggesting that the reaction proceeds via an anionic silicate intermediate rather than a sulfonium enolate. The C3 methoxy substituent is thought to reduce the electrophilicity of the C2 position via π-donation, leading to a highly site-selective substitution. Consistent with this, a mixture of regioisomers was obtained when O- methoxyethyl-2,3-dibromojuglone was used as an electrophile (not shown). Subsequent studies demonstrated that this γ- quinonylation could be extended to an α-quinonylation when enoxysilanes were employed as the nucleophilic component.12 https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.accounts.0c00817 Acc. While the exact mechanism of this trans- formation is not known, it may share parallels with a classic Heck cyclization. The product 23 was found to exist exclusively as the hydroxyfulvene tautomer (as shown). The diazo substituent was introduced in quantitative yield by the treatment of 23 with Hünig’s base and triﬂuoromethanesulfonyl azide.13 Rubottom oxidation of the ketone 24 (triisopropylsilyl triﬂuoromethane- sulfonate then dimethyldioxirane), followed by diastereoselec- tive reduction (borane−tetrahydrofuran) and acidic depro- tection (acetyl chloride, methanol), provided (−)-kinamycin F (1; 29% from 24). Total Synthesis of (−)-Lomaiviticin Aglycon (−)-Lomaiviticins A (25) and B (26) are dimeric, C2-symmetric bacterial metabolites ﬁrst isolated from a strain of Salinispora pacifica.14 (−)-Lomaiviticin A (25) inhibits the growth of cultured human cancer cells, with IC50 values in the low nanomolar to picomolar range. The lomaiviticins contain two diazotetrahydrobenzo[b]ﬂuorene (diazoﬂuorene) residues and are structurally related to the kinamycins, monomeric diazoﬂuorenes isolated from various strains of Stretomyces (vide supra). The cytotoxicity of lomaiviticin A (25) originates from the induction of highly toxic double-strand breaks in DNA.15 To date, there is no completed total synthesis of any of the dimeric lomaiviticins, but several research groups including those of Nicolaou,16 Shair,17 Sulikowski,18 and Feldman19 have reported approaches to access the lomaiviticin skeleton. imeric lomaiviticins, but several research groups including those of Nicolaou,16 Shair,17 Sulikowski,18 and Feldman19 have reported approaches to access the lomaiviticin skeleton. In 2011, we disclosed an enantioselective synthesis of lomaiviticin aglycon (2), the deglycosylated form of 25 and 26.1 The key step in our synthetic strategy involved a late-stage stereoselective oxidative dimerization of two equivalent monomeric diazoﬂuor- enes promoted by manganese tris(hexaﬂuoroacetylacetonate), a potent, non-Lewis acidic single-electron oxidant (Scheme 3).

The synthesis of the monomeric diazoﬂuorene 27 began with 3-(ethylphenoxy)triisopropylsilane (28, prepared in one step from commercial 3-ethylphenol, Scheme 4). The silyl ether 28 was transformed into a 1:1 mixture of C11 hydroxyfulvene diastereomers 29 in seven steps and 30% overall yield. Diazo transfer [triﬂuoromethanesulfonyl azide and 4-(dimethyl- amino)pyridine] produced 30 and 31, the expected monomeric diastereomeric diazoﬂuorenes, which could be separated by ﬂash-column chromatography (51% combined yield). Attempts to transform the endo-mestiyl diazoﬂuorene 30 to (−)-lomai- viticin aglycon (2) were unsuccessful. However, the exo-mesityl diazoﬂuorene 31 was found to undergo oxidative coupling to produce the desired dimerization product 34. Thus, the the exo-mesityl diazoﬂuorene (31) to the conversion of corresponding enoxysilane 32 (trimethylsilyl triﬂuoromethane- sulfonate, triethylamine), followed by oxidative coupling using manganese tris(hexaﬂuoroacetylacetonate) (33) as an oxidant provided the (2R,2′R)-dimer 34 in 26% yield.20 The alternate C2-symmetric (2S,2′S)-dimer 35 was formed in 12% yield and was readily separated from 34. Surprisingly, the third possible product, a C1-symmetric diastereomer, was not observed under these conditions. The stereoselectivity in the oxidative dimerization step is thought to originate from nonbonded interaction between the ortho-methylarene and the C-3 ethyl substituent, as shown in 32. Total Synthesis of (−)-Huperzine A The Lycopodium alkaloids (−)-huperzine A (3) and (−)-hu- perzine B (37) were ﬁrst isolated in 1986 from the Chinese club moss Huperzia serrata21 and were found to be potent, reversible acetylcholinesterase inhibitors (Scheme 5). Of the two, (−)-huperzine A (3) displayed a stronger inhibition activity, with a Ki of 23 nM.22 Owing to this activity and its low toxicity, (−)-huperzine A (3) has found use as a treatment for dementia in China and has been explored as a prophylactic against chemical nerve agents, such as sarin and VX, in the United States. (−)-Huperzine A (3) contains a tricyclic skeleton and four contiguous stereocenters, including an all-substituted carbon center bearing a primary amine. The ﬁrst and second total syntheses of (±)-huperzine A were reported by Kozikowski23 and Ji,24 respectively. Several years later, Kozikowski’s group disclosed an enantioselective route to the target.25 Unfortunately, the clinical development of huperzine in the United States has been impeded by limitations in supply (the producing moss requires 20 years to reach maturity). Many additional synthesis eﬀorts have been disclosed, including modiﬁcations to the Kozikowski route and a multitude of partial, formal, and completed syntheses.26 In 2011, we reported a scalable, enantioselective synthesis of (−)-huperzine A (3). Our synthetic route proceeds via a diastereoselective alkylation of (R)-4-methyl-cyclohex-2-ene-1-one (38) with 3-bromo-2- (bromomethyl)-6-methoxypyridine (39), followed by an intra- molecular enolate α-arylation to form the carbon skeleton.27

Diastereoselective oleﬁnation of the ketone 43 (ethyltriphenylphosphonium bromide, lithium hexa- methyldisilazane) formed the alkene 44 as a 5:1 mixture of E/Z diastereomers (minor diastereomer not shown). To facilitate material throughput, the cyanation and arylation products 42 and 43 were used without puriﬁcation. The alkene 44 was obtained in 71−76% overall yield from the fragment coupling product 41 after puriﬁcation. Oxidative desilylation (triﬂuoro- methanesulfonic acid and then tetrabutylammonium ﬂuoride, hydrogen peroxide, and potassium carbonate) of 44 provided the alcohol 45. Dehydration of 45 with the Burgess reagent (46), followed by platinum-catalyzed nitrile hydrolysis, formed the amide 48. Finally, a Hofmann rearrangement, mediated by bis(triﬂuoroacetoxy)iodobenzene, followed by global depro- tection (trimethylsilyl iodide), provided (−)-huperzine A (3) in 56−70% yield from 44. This route was adapted to a cGMP process by Biscayne Pharmaceuticals and was used to support clinical trials of (−)-huperzine A (3) for the treatment of Dravet syndrome, a rare form of childhood epilepsy. Total Synthesis of Hasubanan Alkaloids

The hasubanan alkaloids are a large family of metabolites isolated from plants of the Stephania genus. They possess a wide range of biological eﬀects, including antiviral,29 antimicrobial,30 and opioid receptor binding activities.31 The targets share a common 7-azatricyclo[4.3.3.01,6]dodecane (propellane) core that contains two vicinal fully-substituted stereocenters and varying substituents on the arene. Several syntheses of (±)-hasubanonine as well as other partial and formal syntheses of hasubanan alkaloids have been disclosed.32 In 2011, we reported the ﬁrst enantioselective syntheses of (−)-hasubano- nine (4), (−)-delavayine (5), (−)-runanine (6), and (+)-peri- https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.accounts.0c00817 Acc. This fragment coupling also served as a point of divergence from intermediate 51 in which diﬀerent hasubanan structures were accessible by varying the structure of the acetylide.

The common intermediate imine 53 was prepared in three steps, with 37% yield and 93% ee from the β-phenethylazide 52 (Scheme 8a). The alkyne pronucleophiles were commercially available or accessible in one step by literature procedures. To access (−)-hasubanonine, the acetylide 56 derived from the alkyne 55 (prepared by a Seyferth−Gilbert homologation of 2- bromo-4,5-dimethoxybenzaldehyde 54) was generated by deprotonation (n-butyllithium). To execute the fragment coupling, the iminium ion 49 was formed in situ by the addition of methyl triﬂate to the imine 53 at −60 °C, followed by the addition of acetylide 56 . Under these conditions, the 1,2- addition product 57 was isolated in 62% yield and was formed as a single detectable diastereomer (1H NMR analysis of the unpuriﬁed product mixture, Scheme 8b). The complex iminium ion, 49, employed here is stabilized by its cyclic structure and the absence of acidic protons adjacent to the C−N double bond. Moreover, selective methylation of the imine renders the C14 carbon more electrophilic than the C6 carbonyl carbon, allowing for the control of siteselectivity in the 1,2-addition. The trimethylsilylcyclopentene auxiliary was then removed from 57 by a thermal retro-cycloaddition reaction (toluene, 135 °C).34 The alkyne was reduced (Crabtree’s catalyst, 58) to form the cis-alkene 59 (53%, two steps). Acid-mediated cyclization (triﬂic acid), aryl bromide reduction (tributyltin hydride), and hydrogenation of the remaining alkene [tris(trimethyl- phosphine)rhodium chloride, triﬂuoroacetic acid, and hydrogen gas] then provided (−)-hasubanonine (4) in three steps (38% overall).

This fragment coupling was adapted to the syntheses of 12 other hasubanan alkaloids and acutumine alkaloids by varying the nature of the acetylide nucleophile (Scheme 9, the magenta atoms correspond to the nucleophilic fragment employed in the coupling).35,36 The route to (−)-acutumine (8) and (−)-dech- loroacutumine (60) proceeded in 14 steps following the fragment coupling reaction. Total Synthesis of (+)-Batzelladine B The guanidinium alkaloids known as the batzelladines (e.g., 61, 62, and 9; Scheme 10) belong to a large family of marine natural products that possess antiproliferative and antiviral activities. (+)-Batzelladine B (9) was isolated in 1995 by Potts and co- workers and was found to inhibit HIV viral entry.37 (+)-Batzelladine B (9) contains a syn-disposed tricyclic guanidine, a bicyclic guanidine, and an alkyl guanidine, all connected via alkyl ester linkages. Numerous syntheses of structurally related guanidinium alkaloids have been reported.38 The strategy we developed proceeded by straightforward disconnection of the ester bond, separating the molecule into fragments 63 and 64, respectively.3 In the approach we pursued, the guanidine residues were ultimately derived from pyrrole- based precursors. https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.accounts.0c00817 Acc. The bicyclic guanidine 64 was synthesized in seven steps and 26% yield from the pyrrole 65 (Scheme 11a). A diastereose- lective 1,2-addition of the enolate derived from 65 to the Ellman sulﬁnimine 6639 provided the β-amino ester 67 in 99% yield with a >20:1 diastereomeric ratio at C2. The C1 center was formed with 94:6 diastereoselectivity, although this is ultimately inconsequential because this center is eventually abolished. Another six steps were required to construct the bicyclic guanidine and introduce the guanidinyl ester to produce 69 in 27% yield from 67. The other bicyclic guanidine 76 was synthesized in six steps and 29% yield from amidinyl pyrrole 70 (Scheme 11b). The key step in that sequence involved a formal [4 + 3] cycloaddition between 70 and (S)-pantolactonyl α-diazo ester 71,40 which provided the dehydrotropanone 72 in 95% yield with a >95:5 diastereomeric ratio. The dehydrotropanone 72 was elaborated to the α-alkynyl-β-ketoester (74) via site- selective reduction (Wilkinson’s catalyst) and α-alkynylation (1- [(trimethylsilyl)ethynyl]-1,2-benziodoxol-3(1H)-one, TMS- Scheme 10. recent studies have established that the epimerization of the C12 quaternary stereocenter, followed by functionalization of the resulting pseudoequatorial alkene, gives rise to compounds having potent activity against Gram-negative pathogens, including drug-resistant Gram-negative strains.43 In 2017, we reported an enantioselective synthesis of several pleuromutilins, including (+)-pleuromutilin (10) and (+)-12- epi-mutilin (12) (Scheme 13).4 Our synthetic strategy was informed by the pioneering syntheses of pleuromutilin by Gibbons,44 Boeckman,45 and Procter46 and by the large body of literature generated in studies of (+)-pleuromutilin (10) by pharmaceutical companies. Germane to our work, researchers at Sandoz Pharmaceuticals had reported47 the reversible isomer- ization of the C12 quaternary center in pleuromutilin via a metal-mediated retroallylation−allylation cascade. This isomer- ization, carried out on the C22 tosylate of (+)-pleuromutilin, provided a 1:1 mixture of the C22 tosylate and its C12 diastereomer. Thus, either (+)-pleuromutilin (10) or (+)-12- epi-pleuromutilin (11) can be accessed by the same synthetic sequence. Our synthetic strategy is based on the late-stage union of the enimide and iodoether fragments, 81 and 82, respectively, to construct the carbon framework.

The enimide fragment 81 was synthesized in eight steps and 20% overall yield from cyclohex-2-ene-1-one (83, Scheme 14a). The conjunctive fragment 82 was prepared from the chiral tigloyl amide (84) in three steps and 32% yield (7:1 diastereomeric ratio in the alkylation step; Scheme 14b). The fragment coupling reaction was achieved by lithium−halogen exchange (tert-butyllithium, −45 °C) of 82, followed by the addition of electrophilic enimide 81 (Scheme 14c). In situ hydrolysis of the resulting lithioenamine (hydrochloric acid, 48%, Scheme 14c) provided the methyl ketone 86 (48%). The methyl ketone product 86 formed in this twofold neopentylic fragment coupling reaction possesses all of the carbons present in the natural product.

To complete the tricyclic pleuromutilin skeleton, the methyl ketone 86 was transformed in three steps to the alkynyl aldehyde 87. The carbon−carbon bond between C10 and C11 was formed via a diastereoselective nickel-catalyzed reductive cyclization of 87 to provide the allylic alcohol 88 in 60% yield and a >20:1 diastereomeric ratio.48 A four-step sequence comprising Dess−Martin oxidation, site- and stereoselective enone reduction, twofold diastereoselective dissolving metal reduction, and acid-catalyzed deprotection then formed (+)-12- epi-mutilin (12, 49% overall). The treatment of (+)-12-epi- mutilin (12) with triﬂuoroacetylimidazole, followed by coupling of the C14 alcohol with O-tritylglycolic acid and acidic deprotection, provided (+)-12-epi-pleuromutilin (11, 57%, three steps). Alternatively, epimerization of the C12 position under conditions adapted from the Sandoz report (diethylzinc), followed by acidiﬁcation with hydrochloric acid, then provided (+)-pleuromutilin (10, 33%). Total Synthesis of (−)-Myrocin G

The myrocins are a small family of secondary fungal metabolites that possess modest antiproliferative and antibiotic activities.49 Structurally, they are distinguished by a tetracyclic framework containing a masked electrophilic cyclopropane, a highly oxidized central ring, and three all-carbon quaternary stereo- centers (C4, C10, and C13, Scheme 15a). The most well known member of this family, (+)-myrocin C (90), was ﬁrst synthesized by Chu-Moyer and Danishefsky in 1992.50 The γ-hydroxy-γ- lactone within (+)-myrocin C (90) is susceptible to ring opening under acidic or basic conditions, and ring and chain related isolates are known (91 and 92).51 isomers of Consequently, we hypothesized that the hitherto unknown chain isomer of (+)-myrocin C (90), which we assigned the trivial name (−)-myrocin G (13), was the biologically active form of myrocin C, and we targeted this for synthesis. The synthetic strategy we developed centered around a convergent fragment coupling−cyclization cascade reaction between iodo- cyclopropane 93 and enoxysilane 94 (Scheme 15b).52 This https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.accounts.0c00817 Acc. The cyclopropyl fragment 93 was prepared in three steps, in 20% yield and 92% ee, from known β-ketoester 95 (Scheme 16a).53 The synthesis of keto enoxysilane 94 was achieved in a total of nine transformations, 5% yield and 95% ee, from the known Diels−Alder adduct 96 (Scheme 16b).54 The fragment coupling−cyclization cascade was initiated by the lithium− halogen exchange (n-butyllithium, −78 °C) of 93 to form the cyclopropyllithium 97. The addition of the enoxysilane 94 then provided, after warming, the tetracyclic product containing the complete carbon skeleton in 38% yield. In studies of this cascade Scheme 16. Further mechanistic studies suggest that the ensuing cyclization is triggered by the migration of the trimethylsilyl substituent (98 → 99), which reveals a C6−C7 enolate that is positioned to undergo an intramolecular aldol addition to generate 100. Activation of the newly formed tertiary alkoxide via carbonate migration (100 → 101) promotes β-elimination and provides fully annulated diosphenol product 102 in 38% yield. To arrive at (−)-myrocin G, 102 was subjected to global deprotection using tetra-n- butylammonium ﬂuoride (64%).

In this section, we analyze the syntheses discussed above from the perspective of convergence, with the goal of identifying useful parameters to quantitate the degree of convergence. It is necessary to note that we are unable to identify a universal system to rank order the degree of convergence of all reported syntheses. Instead, we propose that there are several important criteria that need to be considered and judiciously balanced against each other. The metrics we have chosen, as presented in Figure 2, are the following: A convergent approach should have as few steps as possible. This metric is dedicated to the elegance and ﬂair of the fragment coupling step: it does not have any identiﬁable impact on how convergent an approach is, and the bonds, stereocenters, and rings are typically not of equal signiﬁcance. Nonetheless, this does provide an overall assessment of the complexity generated in the convergent step.

An immediate observation from Figure 2 is the dominance of the syntheses of (−)-lomaiviticin aglycon (2) and (+)-batzella- dine B (9) in the analyses in the metrics. The reason may be obvious: late-stage dimerization and esteriﬁcation, respectively, allow for rather convergent disconnections in the retrosynthetic planning. Eﬀorts in the synthesis of the former can be placed upon synthesizing the monomeric unit itself and the dimerization conditions, and those in the synthesis of the latter can focus on eﬃcient approaches to the individual bicyclic guanidine fragments. This simpliﬁcation allows for less emphasis to be placed on pinpointing the correct fragments, protecting group incompatibilities, and issues of cross-reactivity. An example of a synthesis which suﬀered from those aforemen- tioned diﬃculties is the synthesis of (−)-myrocin G (13), despite having a convergent disconnection into two individual fragments. The synthesis of (−)-myrocin G (13) scores well in the majority of metrics but falls short in the large diﬀerence in the number of steps to each coupling partner, resulting in an inequal, ineﬃcient preparation of keto enoxysilane 94 (13 steps, diﬀerence of 8 steps between the two fragments, Scheme 16a,b). In addition, the fragments involved in the point of convergence were optimized carefully: the ester substituent on cyclopropyl iodide 93 inﬂuences the puriﬁcation of the intermediates and the d. this functional group with the resulting compatibility of lithium−halogen exchange. However, this careful optimization rendered the cascade possible, making three bonds, setting one fully substituted stereocenter, and forming a ring in one step. Similarly, the imbalance of the complexity of fragments evidently exists in the synthesis of (+)-pleuromutilin (10), and neo- pentylic fragment coupling involved elaborate enimide 81 and seemingly simple iodoether 82. This diﬀerence in the step count to each fragment (diﬀerence of ﬁve steps) ultimately arises from the greater complexity of the enimide fragment 81, requiring a longer sequence for construction. Overall, as expected, the molecules with less obvious disconnections for a convergent approach generally score low to middle in metrics, speciﬁcally in the number of steps required after the point of convergence, while the number of carbons united in the fragment coupling step is generally high and a large number of additional steps are required to manipulate the oxidation states, form additional C− C bonds, or remove protecting groups. Nonetheless, this ambiguity allows creativity in the retrosynthetic planning, potentially giving rise to exciting developments in key bond- forming reactions. The concept of convergence has been long understood and applied to the syntheses of complex molecules. In this Account, we introduced several metrics which can further elucidate the nuances behind such an approach, and through an analysis of the completed syntheses from our laboratory based on those metrics, we highlighted some of the strengths and weaknesses of our application of convergence in our past synthesis designs.
